  "response_text": "The mean destock of households starts at a high level, driven by unsustainable initial herd sizes relative to pasture recovery rates. In the early time steps (up to 10–20 years), the metric declines sharply as households rapidly reduce herds to adapt to pasture degradation. This decline reflects the immediate impact of high grazing pressure (livestock-init=90, combined with pasture regeneration rates gr1=0.5 in wet and gr2=0.1 in dry seasons) and climate shocks (rainfall variability with std=100), which exacerbate resource limitations. By 20–50 years, the trend stabilizes at a moderate level, indicating equilibrium herd sizes that balance grazing and biomass recovery. Social-learning agents (E-RO-SL1) and risk-sensitive strategies mitigate further destocking by promoting adaptive herd adjustments, while homogeneous representation of these types accelerates diffusion of effective practices. The stabilization pattern suggests that without intervention (resting?=False), pasture management relies on herd size reductions and behavioral adaptations to cope with stochastic rainfall. Decision-makers should prioritize initial herd limits and controlled grazing intensity to avoid sharp destocking declines, particularly in variable climates."
}

